{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658644"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:52:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:52:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20789"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20789"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.6,0,0.15,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13664"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96007"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13664"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20789"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78747"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"12438"},{"type":"tags","id":"12635"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32883"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32884"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96007"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient with pneumonia undergoes a transbronchial biopsy, which reveals necrotizing pneumonia with a fleur-de-lis pattern, necrotic centres, and hemorrhagic peripheries. Gram-negative bacteria are seen in blood vessel walls with surrounding coagulative necrosis, vasculitis, thrombosis and hemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organisms is most likely causing this patient\u0027s pneumonia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Streptococcus pneumoniae","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Staphylococcus aureus","Haemophilus influenzae","Klebsiella pneumoniae"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely causative organism based on the clinical and histopathological findings. The characteristic features include necrotizing pneumonia with a fleur-de-lis pattern of distribution, pale necrotic centres with hemorrhagic peripheries, and gram-negative bacterial vasculitis with thrombosis. These findings, while not pathognomonic, are highly suggestive of \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E infection. Additionally, \u003Cem\u003EP. aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E is a common respiratory pathogen in patients with cystic fibrosis, often leading to chronic infection despite antibiotic treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are less likely:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes lobar pneumonia with neutrophilic exudate filling alveolar spaces rather than the necrotizing pattern with vascular involvement seen here. \u003Cem\u003ES. pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E is a gram-positive organism, not gram-negative.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKlebsiella pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E, while gram-negative, typically causes a lobar pneumonia with thick, gelatinous sputum and does not characteristically cause the vascular invasion pattern described.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/strong\u003E is a gram-positive organism that can cause necrotizing pneumonia, but does not typically show the vascular tropism described in this case.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/strong\u003E is a gram-negative organism but rarely causes the severe necrotizing pneumonia with vascular invasion described in this case.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn patients with cystic fibrosis, chronic \u003Cem\u003EP. aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E infection can lead to bronchiectasis and pulmonary fibrosis. In severe cases, \u003Cem\u003EP. aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E bacteremia may occur, which can lead to characteristic skin lesions called ecthyma gangrenosum and disseminated intravascular coagulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pseudomonas aeruginosa pneumonia is characterized by necrotizing pneumonia with a fleur-de-lis pattern of distribution through terminal airways.","Histologically, Pseudomonas pneumonia shows gram-negative bacterial vasculitis with thrombosis and hemorrhage.","Pseudomonas aeruginosa is a common complication in cystic fibrosis and can lead to bronchiectasis and pulmonary fibrosis.","Ecthyma gangrenosum is a characteristic skin manifestation of Pseudomonas aeruginosa bacteremia."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; page 366."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78747"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20789"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78747"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-30T14:56:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-30T14:57:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13664"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96007"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.em